<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-767-770  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 767 770.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 20 1990 v24 n34 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The real face of mankind's past: computer scans reveal thatAustralopithecus africanus isn't quite the missing link. (AdvancedTechnology)(includes related article on anthropologists's searchfor appropriate software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nash, Kim S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two Washington University Medical School scientists have mademajor discoveries about the origins of Homo sapiens by workinghard at their computers.andP;  A special computer system which consistsof an Ethernet network of DEC Microvaxes, Siemens InformationSystems Inc scanning equipment and customized software was used topeer inside a rock-filled fossil skull to see what has never beenseen before.andP;  The skull of a two- to three-million-year-oldAustralopithecus africanus, a human-like creature thought to beone of the earliest predecessors of modern Homo sapiens, wasreconstructed by electrically integrating more than 40computerized tomography pictures into one three-dimensional image.andO;Once an image of the skull was on-line it could be electronicallydissected and cross-sectioned for detailed study, a feat thatwould formerly have been impossible without damaging the specimen.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   DEC MicroVAX (Minicomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Research and DevelopmentAnthropologyColleges and UniversitiesWashington, University of. School of MedicineTomographyHuman EvolutionCustom Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>